# Review and QA Rules

## Code Quality

- Keep code readable.
- Prefer explicit names.
- Avoid giant files.
- Avoid deeply nested logic.
- Avoid hidden side effects.
- Avoid magic numbers and unexplained constants.
- Remove unused imports and dead code.
- Keep formatting consistent.

## Error Handling

Every risky operation must handle errors:
- network call
- database operation
- file operation
- parsing/deserialization
- payment/billing/tax/accounting operation
- authentication/authorization
- background job
- sync job

## Validation

Validate:
- user input
- external API response
- environment variables
- file upload
- database payload
- route parameters
- permissions

## Testing

Before finishing:
- Run the project’s relevant analyzer/linter/typecheck/test command.
- If command is unknown, inspect package/config files to identify it.
- If tests do not exist, explain what manual check is needed.

Common commands by ecosystem:
- JavaScript/TypeScript: npm test, npm run lint, npm run typecheck
- Next/Vue/React: npm run lint, npm run build
- Node/Nest/Express: npm test, npm run lint
- Python: pytest, ruff check, mypy
- PHP/Laravel: php artisan test, composer test, pint
- Go: go test ./...
- Rust: cargo test, cargo clippy
- Dart/Flutter: dart analyze, flutter test
- Java/Kotlin: ./gradlew test
